				<section id='statement'>
					<hr class='indent' /><h5>Project Statement</h5>
					<p>Some might view space as the protagonist, but we wanted to challenge the idea that it was some intrinsic aspect of New York’s physical location or design that was responsible for the vitality of the city. Instead, we argue that the light and energy of the city will always be a reflection of the individual. The title for this work, in addition to its relation to the necessary interaction with the sculpture, is a reference to the song “Respiration” by Black Star. </p>

					<blockquote>“I can’t take it y’all, I can feel the city breathin,<br /> chest heavin, against the flesh of the evening<br /> sigh before we die like the last train leaving. <footer>- Respiration, Black Star</footer></blockquote>

					<p>This song uses both micro and macro perspectives on the urban environment to address the idea of the city as a living, breathing creature. Yet the inescapable rhythm of city life, especially New York, is entirely constructed. Rather than continuing to feel victimized by the unstoppable motion of the city, we hope this project provides a sense of hope and motivation for the power of the individual.
					</p>

